Wanted a lower profile ZMR 250 frame that contained all the electronics and wiring. This is the result. This makes use of the ZMR base plate and arms. The rest are set aside from other projects. The back panel on the top is on a hinge for me to access the VTX to change the channels as needed. Use a piece of filament as your hinge pin. Might require a very small amount of boring out. The body and camera bump is designed around a board camera using this 15 degree mount. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1057585 The camera bump is designed to just glue on onto the top plate. Left is separate so that I could adjust a bit. And it allows for a different camera setup later if needed. The landing gear are optional, and make use of the mounting screws that hold the whole body together with some nuts on the bottom. My recommendation is to use only the short screws with the gear so you don't have to mess with the nuts when just removing the top plate. Hardware:

description.text:
UPDATED UPDATE: I've included some pictures of the ever popular twisted vase (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18672) printed in ninjaflex after all the mods and with all the settings mentioned below. This is to show any skeptics that you can in fact print ninjaflex with perfect results on the Duplicator i3. UPDATE: I recently printed dokool's extruder plate located here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1340811
It makes a big difference and I've gotten some pretty complicated prints after installing it in combination with my adapter. With the plate I printed at 20mm/s, 1.00 extrusion multiplier, 1 mm retraction, and an infill overlap of 35%. If you've already printed my adapter i would definetly suggest printing the plate as well. This is a insert for the extruder so that Ninjaflex specifically will work. I don't see why it wouldn't work on other flexible filaments but I've only tested Ninjaflex. The other piece is an adapter for the spool. The standard spool size of Ninjaflex is 2 inches and the Duplicator has a 1.25 " spool holder. To install the extruder insert unscrew the large cooling fan and remove it and the heat sink. Lift the stepper motor up and place the insert with the large hole facing down. It should fit perfectly over the nipple on the extruder base. Definetly use ABS so it doesn't deform from the heat. I've been successful printing with Ninjaflex with 15mm/s speeds with the bed off and the extrusion speed at 60% with a 325% first layer height on buildtak. Also i changed the infill overlap which was 15% on my settings to 30 %.

description.text:
I designed this thing to help convert a battery-powered device to mains power. This design allows you to connect wiring to a d-cell shaped blank. Print as many d-cells as you need to replace batteries.
The blank has small holes in the sides to accept bare wiring. It also has a hole through the long axis and countersinks top and bottom into which you can insert a screw. The screw performs two functions: It provides an electrical contact for the replacement battery and it also secures the bare wire in place. So buy yourself a mains adapter with the same voltage as your batteries, cut off the plug and strip the wire bare for an inch or so. Insert the positive wire into the top of the first blank and the negative wire into the base of the last blank. Secure the wires with screws. I used 10 gauge x 12mm long tec screws, but you can use whatever you have to hand if you drill out the holes to suit.

I printed these things using PLA.

Layer height 0.3mm
Infill 20% Holes are suitable for small gauge DC wiring

title: 2014 Super Tenere Bar stabiliser - work in progress

description.text:
This project is nearing completion, just a few trial fittings and a field test and it will be complete.
The 2014 Yamaha Super tenere has an accessory bar for mounting equipment such as a GPS. this bar is prone to a little bounce/vibration while riding.
Other owners have come up with quite intrusive braces to stabilise the accessory bar and windscreen.
The component I have designed will be largely hidden but provide excellent support.
The 3D printed components are joined together with some 12x3mm aluminium flat bar cut to X length.
The top of the stabiliser clamps to the accessory bar, and the bottom slots over a plastic flange which is part of the headlight and dash assemble. a 4mm home is drilled and a bolt and nut secures the lower bracket.
the Aluminium flat bar is a press fit, and at this stage i am securing it with super glue and filament welded/melted into a countersunk hole.
More details on the assembly of the thing will follow as I move forward and complete the project.
This project has also served as a learning experience for polishing and finishing printed things to get a very smooth and almost commercially manufactured look and feel.

description.text:
This is a tablet clamp designed to be mounted on a 3/8" ballhead, or anything with a 3/8" screw! Started designing it from a need to clamp my new Nexus 7 to my tripod for remote controlling my camera using Helicon Remote. As I finished printing it, I realised it's a damn fine tablet stand for the table. The screw holes to secure the clamp rails are 3.4mm in diameter, which is what you can find on the back of most computer cases. Used two thumbscrews (for easy adjustment) and two normal screws which you can see in the picture. With the right kit such as the Manfrotto Super Clamp and Flex/Magic/Articulating Arm, and a cheap ballhead, this allows you to mount the tablet almost anywhere. Manfrotto Super Clamp
Manfrotto Flex Arm
Manfrotto Articulating Arm
Giotto Ballhead Probably the most useful thing that ever came out of my Makerbot R2! Loving it and creating two more for use at home and in the office. ----- UPDATES -----
Got some ideas on how to improve the clamp, will work on it further. Also, reportedly the triangle jutting out part on the legs might be a bit too short for some with thicker tablets. Have uploaded legs with longer teeth(?) (tripod-tablet-clamp-backplate-legs-longer.stl/skp)

• Print the backplate
  • Print the 4 legs
  • Put rubber pads (cut to size) on the 4 legs.
  • Mount the legs on the backplate.
  • Secure the legs to the backplate using 3.4mm diameter screws.
  • Mount the entire clamp on a cheap ball head.
  • Mount the ballhead+clamp on stand of your choice.
    • Sketchup files are included if you need to amend the screw hole sizes or extend the legs.

description.text:
Thought I'd try to make an extended mag release for my Ruger 10-22 Takedown.  15 cents worth of PETG versus $20-$40 for a commercial one made it seem like a nobrainer to try. 
Is it great?  Eh.  Does it work?  Yes.  Are you going to use it during a zombie apocalypse?  (really?)  But it's good for a range toy and primarily just because. 
NOTE:  This fits over the standard Ruger magazine release. What they call the current shipping extended version, the ones with about a 1/2" of tab that sticks down from the stock in front of the trigger guard. 
On my sample versions of a Ruger magazine release it's a decent friction fit although I'll just put a drop of superglue on it to keep it on there.   You could also drill it and set screw it but that seems a little overkill. 
The purpose is to make it easier to do a magazine change.  You can use your middle finger fairly easily to drop the lever without changing your grip too much.  Note that a Ruger 10-22 is not what you'd call a combat ready weapon, the mags will not drop out unless they're just super loose.  This really is a "just because I have a 3D printer so I can" type build. 
The part that fits over the magazine release is slotted to clear the retention pin on the magazines. 
It fits my Ruger BX25 trigger and the original stock trigger group fairly closely.  It's not 'exact' I just eyeballed it when I was designing in.

Printer:

MendelMax 3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

.25

20%

Notes: Printed fine for me at 240C extruder, 60C bed, 60mm/s with the bed coated with 3DEez. Supports are necessary and can be a bit of a pain to pull out of the hole but they do come using some needle nose with just a bit of persuasion.

Clean out the support and shove it over your magazine release.  If it all looks good and you can release magazines then call it day.  If you want longer term connectivity then clean the magazine release with some barrel blast or brake cleaner or acetone then put a cuople of drops of superglue on it, I use Gorilla superglue gel which seems to work pretty well and then shove the release on it. 
To remove if you super glued it, take your magazine release out of your trigger group and drop it in acetone.

description.text:
This is a planar P3 Penrose tiling designed in OpenScad for MATH 493: Math Through 3D Printing at George Mason University in Fairfax, VA.
The STL files for the patch of tiling and for the individual tiles are included. The tiles are made with extruding and intruding circular arcs to visually show the matching rules for creating Penrose tilings.
A photo of a section of a P3 tiling made in OpenScad is also included, with a hand-drawn image showing the inflation of the tiles. Since this tiling follows both the inflation/deflation rules and the matching rules, we know that this is a Penrose tiling that can continue on infinitely.
The tiling pattern used is a common P3 tiling pattern.
The planar P3 tiling was discovered by Roger Penrose and Robert Ammann separately in the 1970s.

description.text:
A customizable OpenSCAD Sierpinski Tetrix generator. This allows the creation of the Sierpinski Tetrix from tetrahedra, cubes or spheres, but feel free to download the OpenSCAD file to use whatever starting shapes you want.
The script works by translating scaled duplicates of the starting shape with four transformations. The resulting geometry is then scaled, copied, and translated, and this process repeats for any number of iterations. The Customize allows for up to 8 iterations of this process.
EDIT: Code improved for better use of recursion and to allow adustment of the degree of overlap between shapes.
EDIT 2: Fixed a bug where bottom faces had inveted normals when using tetrahedron as base shape.

title: Mendel XLR + Coax power connector bracket (parametric)

description.text: My big power supply that delivers 12V/5A and 18V/15A for the heated print bed via the XLR connector is great, but it's big and noisy due to the cooling fan.  When I'm only printing PLA (which is most of the time) I prefer to use a small, silent and nice looking "laptop replacement" power brick, which I connect via a standard coax power connector.

The SCAD allows you to select XLR, coax or both power connectors. In addition, the dimensions of the connectors is parametric if you have a different connector from mine.
I've provided STLs for all three options with the connector dimensions I used, or you can use the SCAD to customize.
The coax connector I used is a standard "type N" from Radio Shack, 5.5mm outside, 2.5mm inside. Obviously if you get a different power supply you may need a different jack.
When printing the dual connector variant, I found I absolutely HAD to use the "cool" module or the last small bit at the top would look all wonky and have no strength at all.

We found the awesome Textured Earth model by bld and chopped it in half with netfabb Free. Then I used OpenSCAD to increase the size and inset rings which highlight the different layers. We used the measurements from his science textbook and scaled them down for the model so it should be a fairly accurate scale model. Once the rings were done I again used netfabb Free to chop the model into four parts that fit on my Printrbot Simple.
The size of the model is almost 10.5" in diameter.
We are planning on gluing the model together with Loctite 401 glue. My son is going to paint it with Testors model paint.
[Update 2016-02-28] Designed a stand to hold the model. I used M3 screws to attached the small plates to the front of the stand.

description.text:
UPDATED 11/2016!
I've changed the light hood so that it looks like the front cockpit console. Painting the console: The console is a dark grey in the reference pics I have and the rectangles on top are outlined in silver. There are additional silver outlines and details as shown in this screengrab: http://catacombs.space1999.net/main/images/spacehd/tfc/sptfc0021.jpg I've also deepened the wiring channel on the back and increased the LED hole diameter to 6mm to accommodate various LED packages.. LICENSING: This is a copyrighted work. It is offered here for personal, non-commercial use. If you wish to use this design for commercial gain, please contact me for licensing information. If you' just got a 22-inch Eagle Transporter from Round 2, you may decide you want to lit the cockpit interior. I know I do! But I also don't want to go through blacking out the interior and gluing LEDs in place. So I built an insert that can hold two or three 5MM LEDs and direct the light forward without bleeding through the nose, so to speak. There's also a baffle to further direct the light. Glue or solvent weld it to the front of the insert. You can glue a diffuser on it if your LEDs are too bright. See pics for how it goes together. A little hot glue or other thick adhesive to hold it in place and you're all set. 5MM LEDs can be inserted from the back and there are channels to route the wiring back towards the cockpit door. Fill the rear of each hole with putty to block any light leaking from the rear. The rest is up to you. What's that center hole for?
I also put a hole in the middle for a third LED, either for more illumination, a different color or perhaps a color-changing LED.

While it is usually not recommended to print Lego parts (you will still get better quality if you buy them), 3D printers offer the opportunity to customize existing or design new parts. Here is the OpenJSCAD file for (standard) Lego I-Beams - use it as a starting point to create the part you actually need! You may also look at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1358479, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1358484, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1358491 or many others to see some "things" based on this I-Beam script. Note: while this object has been modeled to stand "upright", you may also try to print it "lying" on the print bed (just rotate the model around the x-axis by 90°) - on my printer, the result turned out to be of much better quality than upright and did not require any cleansing after printing (I still have to figure out why)

Within the JSCAD source file, there are a few parameters you may change according to your needs:
  • n specifies the number of cylindric holes in the I-Beam - und, thus, also determines its length. Use a value from 2 on upwards, the biggest suitable value depends on the size of your printer's printbed
    • In this script, n is directly passed to the IBeam function as the HoleCount argument.

description.header: Potential Solutions for Difficulties When Printing
description.text:
Printing a beam on a real 3D printer may reveal some practical problems which have nothing to do with the original modeling of that beam. Nevertheless, there are a few additional modeling parameters which can be used to solve some of these problems.

  • extraWidening can be used to widen the beam holes a bit: since vertically printed walls appear to be a bit "rough" because of the slice structure, Lego pins might become difficult to insert or remove - in that case, some widening of holes may simplify pin usage. By default, extraWidening is set to 0, but you may increase it slightly, e.g. up to 0.1

  • massive: by default, the resulting I-Beam is built based on a "lightBody", which looks like the Lego original, but may be difficult to print as it contains filament "bridges", i.e. parts which do not lay flat on the printbed but start a little bit above. If it turns out, that your printer is unable to print those "bridges" properly, simply change the IBeam invocation to IBeam(n, "massive")

  • xFactor, yFactor, zFactor should usually be set to 1.00 - unless your printer has been poorly configured and needs some scaling in the x, y or z direction. By default, all these factors are set to 1 - in this case, the scaling step is completely skipped, in order to speed up the script a bit. You may, however, try to increase these factors slightly, e.g., up to 1.03

Printed parts usually need some "clean-up" after printing - this especially applies to objects which need to fit other parts.
Personally, I usually take a Dremel 453 ("Chain Saw Sharpening Stone", really) - rotating slowly(!) - to clean the Lego drill holes, but also the "steps" within these holes (especially the lower ones, i.e. those closer to the print bed, as they had to be printed without support structures)
Washing the cleaned parts with pure water removes the dirt and reveals result which can be easily used in combination with standard Lego technic components.

Here are two samples from a program I wrote to create an image wrapped around a cylinder (i.e. a cylindrical projection.) This is fun for art purposes, and I have used it to make fun cookie cutters, molding fondant, making ink stamps, etc. If you want to make your own, you can download the Python program at: https://github.com/lwanger/wrap_image This program will create an STL file for an image of your choosing. Have fun!

Notes: Supports may be necessary depending on the radii used for the model. A smaller difference between the inner and outer radii (the -ir and -or parameters) won't need supports.

How this works... The program is available at: https://github.com/lwanger/wrap_image This program reads an image in using the Python image library (PIL). It then converts the image into a height field in cylindrical coordinates (takes the pixel value from 0 to 255 and linearly interpolates it from the inner radius to the outer radius.) It then creates triangles for all of these and spits it out as an STL. file. You will need Python with PIL and NumPy to create these.

The IKEA BILLY is perhaps their best-selling, and definitely their most versatile, bookcase system. For reasons that I fail to grasp, they don't have holes everywhere, so if you want shelves with non-standard spacing, you need to drill them yourself. The idea behind this jig is to use the existing holes to align it, and provide a guide for the drill bit to drill holes that are perpendicular to the surface. Moreover, you don't want the drill bit going all the way through, so the height of the jig should be set according to the length of the drill bit and how deeply it sits in the chuck. I am not providing an STL file, as it is almost certain that your combination of drill bit / drill will need a different offset. Also: if you live in the USA and cannot find metric bits, the closest size to an IKEA pin is a 13/64''. You may get away with a 3/8'' and a bit of hammering.
